{"cursor":"4095","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name=New High German |nativename=Teutsch, Deutsch,\nNeuhochdeutsch |states=Germany, Austria, Luxembourg, Liechtenstein, Switzerland,\nNetherlands , Israel |region= |speakers=90 to 120 million\n|date=1990 |ref= SIL Ethnologue (2009). 90 million speakers of Standard\nGerman; 120 million including Middle and Upper German dialects; 122 million\nincluding Yiddish. {{cite book |authorlink = National\nGeographic |title = National Geographic Collegiate Atlas of the World |publisher\n= R.R Donnelley & Sons Company |date = 2006 |month = April |location = Willard,\nOhio |pages = 257â270 |isbn = Regular:0-7922-3662-9, 978-0-7922-3662-7. Deluxe:0-7922-7976-\nX, 978-0-7922-7976-1 }} |speakers2=Non-native speakers: 20 million |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=Germanic |fam3=West Germanic\n|fam4=High German |ancestor=Old High German |ancestor2=Middle High German\n|ancestor3=Early New High German |script=German alphabet |nation=Austria,\nEuropean Union, Germany, Liechtenstein, Luxembourg, Switzerland, Belgium, co-\nofficial language of Namibia until 1990. |iso1=de |iso2b=ger |iso2t=deu |ld1 =\nStandard German |lc1 = deu |ld2 = Upper Saxon |lc2 = sxu |ld3 = Upper Silesian\n|lc3 = sli |ld4 = Wymysorys |lc4 = wym |ld5 = Frankish |lc5 = frk |ld6 =\nLuxembourgeois |lc6 = ltz |ld7 = MainfrÃ¤nkisch |lc7 = vmf |ld8 = Limburgish |lc8\n= lim |ld9 = Pfaelzisch |lc9 = pfl |ld10 = KÃ¶lsch |lc10 = ksh |ld11 =\nPennsylvania German |lc11 = pdc |ld12 = Colonia Tovar German |lc12 = gct |ld13 =\nSwiss German |lc13 = gsw |ld14 = Swabian |lc14 = swg |ld15 = Walser |lc15 = wae\n|ld16 = Bavarian |lc16 = bar |ld17 = Cimbrian |lc17 = cim |ld18 = Hutterisch\n|lc18 = geh |ld19 = MÃ³cheno |lc19 = mhn |ld20 = Eastern Yiddish |lc20 = ydd\n|ld21 = Western Yiddish |lc21 = yih }} 'New High German' (NHG) is the term used\nfor the most recent period in the history of the German language. It is a\ntranslation of the German Neuhochdeutsch (Nhd). It includes all of the modern\nHigh German dialects since the Baroque period, but is often used as a synonym\nfor Standard German.\n\nThe German term was originally coined in 1848 by Jacob Grimm for the period from\n1500 to the present day, following on from Middle High German\n(Mittelhochdeutsch). However, Wilhelm Scherer redefined it as the period from\n1650, introducing a new term FrÃ¼hneuhochdeutsch (Early New High German) for the\nperiod 1350-1650, and this is the most widely adopted periodisation of German.\nIn this sense, the beginning of New High German is marked by the \"first German\nnovel\", Grimmelshausen's [[Simplicius Simplicissimus]].\n\nThe New High German period is characterised by the codification of German\ngrammar and the development of a standard language in both writing and speech.\nUnlike earlier periods, there have been few major changes in phonology or\nmorphology. Rather, the standard language has selected particular features and\nthese choices have then exerted an influence on individual German dialects.\n","linknr":168,"url":"Modern_German","recorded":1374966016,"links":["/w/index.php?title=New_High_German&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=New_High_German&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/New_High_German","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoi